<li id="cite_note-70"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-70">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFOrchardRiley1987" class="citation book cs1">Orchard, Bernard; Riley, Harold (1987). <i>The Order of the Synoptics: Why Three Synoptic Gospels?</i>. p.&#160;172. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0865542228" title="Special:BookSources/0865542228"><bdi>0865542228</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Order+of+the+Synoptics%3A+Why+Three+Synoptic+Gospels%3F&amp;rft.pages=172&amp;rft.date=1987&amp;rft.isbn=0865542228&amp;rft.aulast=Orchard&amp;rft.aufirst=Bernard&amp;rft.au=Riley%2C+Harold&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APapias+of+Hierapolis" class="Z3988"></span> "…has three divisions: (1) Sections l–8a are concerned with Eusebius's attempt to use Papias's preface to his five books of… Thirdly, Eusebius knew that Irenaeus believed Papias to be a reliable witness to the original apostolic tradition."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-71"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-71">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFDavies_and_Allison" class="citation book cs1">Davies and Allison. <i>A Critical and Exegetical Commentary on the Gospel according to Saint Matthew, Volume 1, ICC</i>. p.&#160;13.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=A+Critical+and+Exegetical+Commentary+on+the+Gospel+according+to+Saint+Matthew%2C+Volume+1%2C+ICC&amp;rft.pages=13&amp;rft.au=Davies+and+Allison&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APapias+of+Hierapolis" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-72"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-72">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFBlack1994" class="citation book cs1">Black, C. Clifton (1994). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/markimagesofapos00blac/page/86"><i>Mark: Images of an Apostolic Interpreter</i></a>. p.&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/markimagesofapos00blac/page/86">86</a>. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0872499731" title="Special:BookSources/0872499731"><bdi>0872499731</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Mark%3A+Images+of+an+Apostolic+Interpreter&amp;rft.pages=86&amp;rft.date=1994&amp;rft.isbn=0872499731&amp;rft.aulast=Black&amp;rft.aufirst=C.+Clifton&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fdetails%2Fmarkimagesofapos00blac%2Fpage%2F86&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APapias+of+Hierapolis" class="Z3988"></span> "quoted Papias and took him so seriously, if his theology was such an embarrassment. The answer may be that Papias… None of this, naturally, is tantamount to an assessment of Papias's reliability, on which we are not yet prepared to pass."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-73"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-73">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFEhrman2006" class="citation book cs1"><a href="/wiki/Bart_D._Ehrman" title="Bart D. Ehrman">Ehrman, Bart D.</a> (2006). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/peterpaulmarymag00ehrm_0/page/8"><i>Peter, Paul, and Mary Magdalene: The Followers of Jesus in History and Legend</i></a>. p.&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/peterpaulmarymag00ehrm_0/page/8">8</a>. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0195300130" title="Special:BookSources/0195300130"><bdi>0195300130</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Peter%2C+Paul%2C+and+Mary+Magdalene%3A+The+Followers+of+Jesus+in+History+and+Legend&amp;rft.pages=8&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.isbn=0195300130&amp;rft.aulast=Ehrman&amp;rft.aufirst=Bart+D.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fdetails%2Fpeterpaulmarymag00ehrm_0%2Fpage%2F8&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APapias+of+Hierapolis" class="Z3988"></span> "The reason this matters for our purposes here is that one of the few surviving quotations from Papias's work provides a reference to…. But unfortunately, there are problems with taking Papias's statement at face value and assuming that in Mark's Gospel we have a historically reliable account of the activities of Peter. To begin with, some elements of Papias's statement simply aren't plausible."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-74"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-74">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFBauckham2007" class="citation book cs1"><a href="/wiki/Richard_Bauckham" title="Richard Bauckham">Bauckham, Richard</a> (2007). <i>The Testimony of the Beloved Disciple: Narrative, History, and Theology in the Gospel of John</i>. p.&#160;53. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0801034855" title="Special:BookSources/978-0801034855"><bdi>978-0801034855</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Testimony+of+the+Beloved+Disciple%3A+Narrative%2C+History%2C+and+Theology+in+the+Gospel+of+John&amp;rft.pages=53&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.isbn=978-0801034855&amp;rft.aulast=Bauckham&amp;rft.aufirst=Richard&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APapias+of+Hierapolis" class="Z3988"></span> "Much discussion of Papias's comments about Mark and Matthew, preoccupied either with showing their reliability as evidence for the origins of these Gospels or with emphasizing their apologetic character in order to discredit their reliability…."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-75"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-75">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFPark2009" class="citation book cs1">Park, Yoon-Man (2009). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=qVlIPa_zUJYC&amp;pg=PA50"><i>Mark's Memory Resources and the Controversy Stories (Mark 2:1-3:6): An Application of the Frame Theory of Cognitive Science to the Markan Oral-Aural Narrative</i></a>. p.&#160;50. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-9004179622" title="Special:BookSources/978-9004179622"><bdi>978-9004179622</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Mark%27s+Memory+Resources+and+the+Controversy+Stories+%28Mark+2%3A1-3%3A6%29%3A+An+Application+of+the+Frame+Theory+of+Cognitive+Science+to+the+Markan+Oral-Aural+Narrative&amp;rft.pages=50&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.isbn=978-9004179622&amp;rft.aulast=Park&amp;rft.aufirst=Yoon-Man&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DqVlIPa_zUJYC%26pg%3DPA50&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APapias+of+Hierapolis" class="Z3988"></span> "Before using this source as evidence it is necessary to discuss the much debated issue of the reliability of Papias's testimony. Many modern scholars have dismissed the reliability of the tradition from Papias primarily because they believe it was formulated to vindicate the apostolicity of Mark's Gospel. Yet what is to be noted is that Papias's claim to apostolicity for the second Gospel is indirectly made through Peter rather than through Mark himself. The question is that if Papias wished to defend the apostolicity of Mark's Gospel, why did he not directly appeal to apostolic authorship… instead of fabricating the relationship between Mark and Peter? Besides…"</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-76"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-76">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFCasey2010" class="citation book cs1"><a href="/wiki/Maurice_Casey" title="Maurice Casey">Casey, Maurice</a> (2010). <i>Jesus of Nazareth: An Independent Historian's Account of His Life and Teaching</i>. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0567104083" title="Special:BookSources/978-0567104083"><bdi>978-0567104083</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Jesus+of+Nazareth%3A+An+Independent+Historian%27s+Account+of+His+Life+and+Teaching&amp;rft.date=2010&amp;rft.isbn=978-0567104083&amp;rft.aulast=Casey&amp;rft.aufirst=Maurice&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APapias+of+Hierapolis" class="Z3988"></span> "It was later Church Fathers who confused Matthew's collections of sayings of Jesus with our Greek Gospel of Matthew. I suggest that a second source of the confusion lay with the real author of this Gospel. One possibility is that he was also called Matthias or Matthew. These were common enough Jewish names, and different forms were similar enough."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTEMacDonald2012-77"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMacDonald2012_77-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFMacDonald2012">MacDonald 2012</a>.</span>
</li>
